<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Deferred Compensation </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In 2014,
our NEOs were eligible to participate in the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Executive Deferred Compensation Plan (&#147;MEDCP&#148;), a voluntary non-qualified deferred compensation plan. The program is similar to those provided to executive officers at
many of the companies in our Compensation Survey Group and is provided for recruitment purposes and to assist executives in managing their future cash flow. The deferred compensation plan provides an opportunity for executives to defer, on a pre-tax
basis, up to 50% of their salary and up to 100% of their award under the Annual Cash Incentive Program. Executives may invest deferred amounts in one or more notional investment options. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Executive Perquisites </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We offer our NEOs executive physicals and allowances
for car and financial counseling expenses. Additionally, based on the findings of an independent, third-party security study, we require Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld to use the corporate aircraft for business and personal travel. This also allows
Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld to be more productive and efficient when she travels, particularly considering we do business in approximately 165 countries. NEOs are solely responsible for all taxes on all perquisites. We do not provide tax gross ups. We offer
types of perquisites similar to those offered by companies in our Compensation Survey Group and do so at comparable costs. The Compensation Committee believes that these perquisites are important for retention and recruitment. The footnotes to the
Summary Compensation Table under &#147;Executive Compensation Tables&#148; list specific executive officer perquisites. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Retirement and Separation Benefits
</B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As described below, we offer our NEOs retirement and separation benefits. We do not have employment agreements with any of our NEOs. They are all &#147;at
will&#148; employees, including Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Retirement Benefits </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Generally, our NEOs are eligible for broad-based U.S. employee benefit plans, including two tax-qualified plans&#151;the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Retirement Plan
(&#147;Retirement Plan&#148;) and the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Thrift Plan (&#147;Thrift Plan&#148;). U.S. employees hired after 2008 are not eligible to participate in the Retirement Plan or the defined benefit portion of the Supplemental Plan (as
defined below). In addition, accruals under the Retirement Plan and the defined benefit portion of the Supplemental Plan will cease after 2019. U.S. employees hired after 2008 who are not eligible to participate in the Retirement Plan are eligible
to receive an enhanced employer contribution under the Thrift Plan and the defined contribution portion of the Supplemental Plan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We also provide an unfunded
non-qualified plan, the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan (&#147;Supplemental Plan&#148;), for eligible U.S. employees. The Supplemental Plan provides benefits that are not able to be provided under the Retirement Plan or Thrift
Plan due to an employee&#146;s compensation exceeding the tax-qualified plan compensation limit under Code Section&nbsp;401(a)(17), an employee&#146;s election to defer compensation under either the MEDCP or the Supplemental Plan, or a Retirement
Plan participant&#146;s benefit exceeding the limits under Section&nbsp;415 of the Code. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We provide Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld with a non-qualified, enhanced pension
benefit that credits her pension service for the period of time (2004-2006) that she was not employed by us. We provide this enhanced pension benefit to Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld because, when she rejoined the Company, she forfeited her right to a pension
benefit at her previous employer. This benefit was part of a broader incentive program to help encourage her to return to the Company and become our CEO. The 2014 Pension Benefits table and the accompanying narrative to the table under
&#147;Executive Compensation Tables&#148; provide additional details about this benefit. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Compensation Committee believes the Retirement Plan, Thrift Plan and
non-qualified Supplemental Plan are integral parts of our overall executive compensation program. The Compensation Committee believes our NEOs should receive the same defined benefit accruals, be able to defer the same percentage of their
compensation and receive the same corresponding notional employer contributions, as all other employees, without regard to the Code&#146;s compensation limit applicable to tax-qualified plans or whether the NEO has elected to defer compensation.
</P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;53 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Change in Control Plan </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have
a Change in Control Plan (the &#147;CIC Plan&#148;) for senior executive officers. The CIC Plan is consistent with similar plans maintained by companies in our Compensation Survey Group, including eligibility, severance benefit levels and treatment
of cash and performance-based equity compensation. We structure separation payments to help assure that key personnel, including our NEOs, would be available to assist in the successful transition following a change in control and provide a
competitive level of severance protection if the executive officer is involuntarily terminated without cause or resigns for good reason within two years following a change in control (&#147;double trigger&#148;). In the event that a payment under
the CIC Plan triggers an excise tax under Code Section&nbsp;4999, the payment will be the greater of the full benefit or a reduced benefit that does not trigger the excise tax as determined on an after-tax basis for each. We do not provide any tax
gross ups for taxes payable on change in control benefits. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We describe the severance arrangements and other benefits provided under the CIC Plan (as well as the
equity treatment upon certain separations in the event of a change in control) under &#147;Executive Compensation Tables &#150; Potential Payments upon Termination or Change in Control.&#148; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Non-Change in Control Severance Agreements </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Although we generally do not have
individual severance or employment agreements with any of our NEOs, we would typically provide separation benefits as consideration for entering into an agreement protecting our interests. The severance payments and other benefits provided to a
typical NEO are described under &#147;Executive Compensation Tables &#150; Potential Payments upon Termination or Change in Control.&#148; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Compensation Paid to our Named Executive Officers in 2014 </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Overview </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The chart below shows specific 2014 compensation actions for each
NEO, except for Mr.&nbsp;Gladden. Mr.&nbsp;Gladden&#146;s compensation is discussed separately in his individual section below. For the shares awarded under the 2012-2014 performance cycle, see &#147; &#150; Description of Individual Executive
Compensation Program Elements &#150; Equity Program &#150; 2012-2014 Performance Cycle&#148; above. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld&#146;s 2014-2016 performance share unit target opportunity is a percentage of her base salary based on her role. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Defined Benefit Pension
Present Value Increase </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As disclosed in the 2014 Summary Compensation Table under &#147;Executive Compensation Tables,&#148; the present value of Ms.
Rosenfeld&#146;s defined benefit pension increased from the prior year. The primary driver of the present value increase is the decrease in the applicable discount rate, which resulted in a present value increase of approximately $3.0 million. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mr.&nbsp;Gladden </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Commencement of Employment </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Gladden commenced employment as an Executive Vice President on October&nbsp;13, 2014 and became our Chief Financial Officer effective December&nbsp;1, 2014. To
incent him to join the Company and provide additional relocation assistance, the Compensation Committee approved a one-time cash payment of $500,000 that is subject to full repayment if his employment with us terminates before October&nbsp;13, 2017
(except for an involuntary termination without cause or termination due to death or disability). To provide him additional incentive to join the Company and because we hired Mr.&nbsp;Gladden after the 2014 annual equity grant, we sought to
immediately align his compensation with our key critical performance measures and the interests of shareholders. Therefore, our Compensation Committee made him a one-time performance-based equity grant of 68,230 performance share units and 341,120
NQSOs (with a combined grant value of $4,500,253). The one-time performance-based equity grant only rewards Mr.&nbsp;Gladden upon achievement of certain performance metrics (performance share units) or if there is an increase in our share price
(NQSOs). The performance share units vest and are subject to the same terms and conditions as the performance share unit grants made to our executives on February&nbsp;18, 2015 for the 2015-2017 performance cycle with the exception that the
performance share units pro rata vest based on actual performance upon an involuntary termination without cause. The performance share unit grants to our executives on February&nbsp;18, 2015 contain the same performance measures and targets as the
performance share units granted for the 2014-2016 performance cycle, which are described above. The NQSOs are generally subject to the same terms as the grants made to the NEOs on February&nbsp;19, 2014 and vest 33%&nbsp;per year for the first two
years on the anniversary of the grant date and the remaining 34% on the third anniversary of the grant date. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;55 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Target Total Direct Compensation </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Gladden&#146;s target compensation levels are above the median of our Compensation Survey Group primarily because he has significant prior operating experience
and his responsibilities as Chief Financial Officer are broader than the typical Chief Financial Officer role, extending to operating excellence including our Zero Based Budgeting initiatives. Mr.&nbsp;Gladden&#146;s annual base salary is $900,000
and his target annual incentive is 100% of his base salary. Because he joined the Company in the fourth quarter of 2014, Mr.&nbsp;Gladden received a prorated annual incentive for 2014 based on actual performance at a level no less than target. Due
to above target Company performance, he received an above target prorated 2014 annual incentive award equal to $247,000. Mr.&nbsp;Gladden&#146;s target annual equity grant value is $4,700,000. The Compensation Committee made his first annual equity
grant at target on February&nbsp;18, 2015, the same time as the 2015 annual equity grant was made to employees generally. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mr.&nbsp;Brearton </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Base Salary </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Brearton did not receive a salary increase in 2014. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>2014 Annual Cash Incentive Program Award </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Brearton&#146;s 2014
individual performance rating primarily reflects our overall financial performance relative to target and a successful CFO transition. Mr.&nbsp;Brearton was also a leader in our cost cutting initiatives and was instrumental in reaching an agreement
with D.E Master Blenders 1753 B.V. to form a joint venture, which we announced in mid-2014. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>2014 Equity Grant (Restricted Stock, Non-Qualified Stock Options and
Performance Share Units) </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Brearton&#146;s equity grant reflects his long-term performance and external market positioning. Mr.&nbsp;Brearton&#146;s
2014-2016 performance share unit target opportunity is a percentage of his base salary based on his role. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mr.&nbsp;Abelenda </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Base Salary </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Abelenda did not receive a salary increase in 2014. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>2014 Annual Cash Incentive Program Award </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Abelenda&#146;s 2014
individual performance rating primarily related to his leadership in delivering strong business results across the Latin America region, which exceeded its 2014 financial targets despite volatility in key markets such as Venezuela and Argentina.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>2014 Equity Grant (Restricted Stock, Non-Qualified Stock Options and Performance Share Units) </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Abelenda&#146;s equity grant reflects his long-term performance and external market positioning. Mr.&nbsp;Abelenda&#146;s 2014-2016 performance share unit
target opportunity is a percentage of his base salary based on his role. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mr.&nbsp;Clouse </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Base Salary </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Clouse received a salary increase in April 2014 based on
his individual performance assessment and a salary increase in July 2014 coincident with his appointment as Chief Growth Officer. Both increases took into account his individual performance assessment and internal and external market positioning.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>2014 Annual Cash Incentive Program Award </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Clouse&#146;s 2014
individual performance rating primarily related to the business results for the North America region and his additional responsibilities as Chief Growth Officer. Despite a challenging operating environment, the North America region held its
aggregate market share compared to 2013 and continued to aggressively manage overhead costs. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>2014 Equity Grant (Restricted Stock, Non-Qualified Stock Options and Performance Share Units) </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Clouse&#146;s equity grant reflects his long-term performance and potential and external market positioning. Mr.&nbsp;Clouse&#146;s 2014-2016 performance share
unit target opportunity is a percentage of his base salary based on his role. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mr.&nbsp;Cofer </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Base Salary </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Cofer received a modest salary increase in April 2014
based on his individual performance assessment. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>2014 Annual Cash Incentive Program Award </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Cofer&#146;s 2014 individual performance rating primarily related to the business results for the Asia Pacific region. Asia Pacific performed below target in
2014; however, notable progress was made in key growth markets setting the region up for future success. Performance in our Eastern Europe, Middle East and Africa region was solid despite economic and political instability in the region. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>2014 Equity Grant (Deferred Stock Units, Non-Qualified Stock Options and Performance Share Units) </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Cofer&#146;s equity grant reflects his long-term performance and potential and external market positioning. Mr.&nbsp;Cofer&#146;s 2014-2016 performance share
unit target opportunity is a percentage of his base salary based on his role. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>International Assignment Payments </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As a U.S. expatriate, Mr.&nbsp;Cofer received payments in 2014 in conjunction with his international assignment based in Singapore. These payments to Mr.&nbsp;Cofer were
similar to the types of payments generally made to other employees who accept an international assignment with the Company under our International Assignment Policy. Our International Assignment Policy is designed to facilitate relocation of
employees to positions in other countries by covering expenses over and above those that the employees would have incurred had they remained in their home countries. Such payments include housing expenses, cost of living adjustment, education and
travel expenses. Similarly, our International Assignment Policy covers the additional taxes employees incur due solely to their international assignments. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Ms.&nbsp;West </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Base Salary </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Ms.&nbsp;West received a modest increase in April 2014 based on her individual performance assessment. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>2014 Annual Cash Incentive Program Award </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Ms.&nbsp;West&#146;s 2014
individual performance rating primarily related to her transition of responsibilities. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>2014 Equity Grant (Restricted Stock, Non-Qualified Stock Options and
Performance Share Units) </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Ms.&nbsp;West&#146;s equity grant reflects her external market positioning. Ms.&nbsp;West&#146;s 2014-2016 performance share unit
target opportunity is a percentage of her base salary based on her role. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Departure </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In July 2014, we announced that Ms.&nbsp;West will depart from the Company. We anticipate she will depart in September 2015 following a successful transition of her
responsibilities. Ms.&nbsp;West&#146;s separation details are described under &#147;Executive Compensation Tables &#150; Potential Payments upon Termination or Change in Control.&#148; </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Policy Authorizing Recoupment of Executive Incentive Compensation in the </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Event of Certain Restatements </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board or an appropriate
committee of the Board may determine that, as a result of a restatement of our financial statements, an executive officer received more compensation than the executive officer would have received absent the incorrect financial statements. The Board
or committee, in its discretion, may then take such actions as it deems necessary or appropriate to address the events that gave rise to the restatement and to prevent its recurrence. Such actions may include, to the extent permitted by applicable
law: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">requiring the executive officer to repay some or all of any bonus or other incentive compensation paid; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">requiring the executive officer to repay any gains realized on the exercise of stock options or on the open-market sale of vested shares; </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">canceling some or all of the executive officer&#146;s restricted stock or deferred stock unit grants, performance share units and outstanding stock options; </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">adjusting the executive officer&#146;s future compensation; or </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">terminating or initiating legal action against the executive officer. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Trading Restrictions and
Anti-Hedging Policy </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our insider trading policy limits the timing and types of transactions in Mondel&#275;z International securities by Section&nbsp;16
officers, including our NEOs (and any member of the Section&nbsp;16 officer&#146;s family sharing the same household). Among other restrictions, the policy: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">allows Section&nbsp;16 officers to trade company securities only during open window periods (following earnings releases) and only after they have pre-cleared transactions; </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">prohibits Section&nbsp;16 officers from short-selling company securities or &#147;selling against the box&#148; (failing to deliver sold securities); and </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">prohibits Section&nbsp;16 officers from entering into transactions in puts, calls or other derivatives on Mondel&#275;z International securities on an exchange or in any other organized market, as well as any other
derivative or hedging transactions on Mondel&#275;z International securities. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Anti-Pledging Policy </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our insider trading policy prohibits our directors, executive officers and certain additional executives from holding Mondel&#275;z International securities in a margin
account or pledging Mondel&#275;z International securities as collateral for a loan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Policy with Respect to Qualifying Compensation for Tax
Deductibility </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Code Section&nbsp;162(m) limits our ability to deduct compensation paid to certain NEOs (the &#147;covered employees&#148;) to $1.0 million
annually. Covered employees under Code Section&nbsp;162(m) include our principal executive officer and our next three highest paid executive officers, other than our principal financial officer. This limitation does not apply to performance-based
compensation, provided certain conditions are satisfied. The Company strives to have the Annual Cash Incentive Program awards and awards under our equity program qualify as performance-based compensation and thus tax-deductible under Code
Section&nbsp;162(m). However, the application of Section&nbsp;162(m) is complex and may change with time (with a potentially retroactive effect) and thus there can be no guarantee that all of these awards will actually qualify as performance-based
compensation under Section&nbsp;162(m). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Additionally, the Compensation Committee retains the discretion to authorize payments that may not be tax-deductible if it
believes such payments are in the best interest of shareholders. For example, the Compensation Committee decided, based on benchmarking salaries of other chief executive officers in the Compensation Survey Group, to pay Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld an annual
base salary in excess of $1.0 million. Therefore, a portion of her salary was not tax-deductible in 2014. In addition, a portion of certain of the other covered employees&#146; income exceeded the $1.0 million tax deductibility limit for 2014
because of other elements of their annual compensation. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;58 </FONT></P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(a)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Consistent with the findings of an independent, third-party security study, for security and personal safety, we require Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld to use our aircraft for all travel. The incremental cost of personal use of our
aircraft, as reflected in the table, includes the cost of trip-related crew hotels and meals, in-flight food and beverages, landing and ground handling fees, hourly maintenance contract costs, hangar or aircraft parking costs, fuel costs based on
the average annual cost of fuel per hour flown, and other smaller variable costs. Fixed costs that would be incurred in any event to operate our aircraft (for example, aircraft purchase costs, maintenance not related to personal trips and flight
crew salaries) are not included in the incremental cost of Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld&#146;s use of our aircraft. Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld is responsible for taxes in connection with her personal use of our aircraft and we do not reimburse her for those taxes.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(b)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">All executive officers are eligible for an annual financial counseling allowance up to $7,500 and, in the case of Ms. Rosenfeld, up to $10,000. For Mr. Gladden, the amount also includes a one-time $14,000 reimbursement
for legal expenses in connection with his hire. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

provided to cover the additional taxes due solely to the relocation assistance program in accordance with the policy. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(d)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Mr. Cofer, a U.S. expatriate, received payments in conjunction with his international assignment based in Singapore.&nbsp;These payments to Mr. Cofer were similar to the types of payments generally made to other
employees who accept an international assignment with the Company. The payments are designed to facilitate the relocation of employees to positions in other countries by covering expenses over and above those that employees accepting assignments
would have incurred had they remained in their home countries.&nbsp;These payments include housing expenses, cost of living adjustment, schooling and travel expenses.&nbsp;Similarly, the tax payments are made pursuant to our International Assignment
Policy, which is designed to cover the additional taxes that an employee incurs due solely to the international assignment. The tax equalization amount is negative due to the amount and timing of repayments related to tax equalization settlements.
</TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

performance cycle and will be paid out in cash based on the actual number of shares earned for the performance cycle, if any. The maximum payout equals 200% of target. </TD></TR></TABLE>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(4)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For stock options granted prior to May&nbsp;21, 2014, the exercise price equals the average of the high and low share price of our common stock on the grant date. As a result, stock options granted on February&nbsp;19,
2014 have a slightly lower exercise price than the closing stock price on the grant date of $34.26. For stock options granted on or after May&nbsp;21, 2014, the exercise price equals the closing price of our common stock on the grant date.
</TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(5)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The amounts represent the grant date fair value of the awards as computed in accordance with FASB ASC Topic 718. </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;63 </FONT></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Retirement Benefit Plan Descriptions </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondel&#275;z Global
LLC Retirement Plan </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Beginning January&nbsp;1, 2009, this program is not offered to newly hired U.S. employees. However, all eligible full-time and part-time
U.S. employees hired before January&nbsp;1, 2009, including our NEOs (except Mr.&nbsp;Gladden), are covered automatically in our funded non-contributory, tax-qualified defined benefit plan. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Benefits under this plan are payable upon retirement in the form of an annuity or a lump sum (if the employee was hired before 2004). Normal retirement under this plan
is defined as age 65 with five years of vesting service, at which point participants are eligible to receive an unreduced benefit. Vested participants may elect to receive benefits before age 65, but the amount is reduced as benefits are paid over a
longer period of time. Participants must have at least five years of service to become vested. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The formula used to calculate a benefit is equal to the following:
</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">1.3% of final average pay up to the Social Security covered compensation amount multiplied by years of service up to 30; plus </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">1.675% of final average pay in excess of the Social Security covered compensation amount, multiplied by years of service up to 30; plus </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">0.5% of final average pay multiplied by years of service in excess of 30. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Final average pay is defined as the greater
of (a)&nbsp;the average of an executive officer&#146;s salary plus annual bonus during the last 60 consecutive months of service before separation and (b)&nbsp;the five highest consecutive calendar years of salary plus annual bonus out of the last
ten years prior to separation. Social Security covered compensation is an amount equal to the average of the Social Security taxable wage bases for the 35-year period that ends in the year the participant reaches age 65. (If the participant was born
between 1938 and 1954, the 35-year average ends in the year the participant reaches age 66. If the participant was born after 1954, the 35-year average ends in the year the participant reaches age 67.) The Internal Revenue Service has established
certain limits on how much employees may receive from this plan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As of December&nbsp;31, 2014, Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld is eligible to retire under the Mondel&#275;z
Global LLC Retirement Plan. Employees hired before January&nbsp;1, 2004 with at least ten years of service are eligible to retire under this plan at age&nbsp;55. The benefits payable to employees eligible to retire before age 62 are reduced by 3%
each year (maximum 20%) between age 62 and the year that the employee retires. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan I </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Code limits the amount employees may receive from the tax-qualified pension plan. Therefore, we offer a supplemental defined benefit pension program under the
Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan I. Beginning January&nbsp;1, 2009, this program is not offered to newly hired U.S. employees. However, all eligible full-time and part-time U.S. employees hired before January&nbsp;1, 2009,
including our NEOs (except Mr.&nbsp;Gladden), may participate in this unfunded program that provides for the difference between what would have been payable based upon the pension plan formula stated above absent the applicable Code limits and the
amount actually payable from the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Retirement Plan. Additionally, any eligible base salary and annual cash incentive deferrals made under the voluntary non-qualified deferred compensation plan are considered non-qualified
earnings and are subsequently paid out under this program regardless of whether or not the executive exceeds the applicable Code limits. Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld is eligible to retire under the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan I.
Employees hired before January&nbsp;1, 2004 with at least ten years of service are eligible to retire under this plan at age 55. The benefits payable to employees eligible to retire before age 62 are reduced by 3% each year (maximum 20%) between age
62 and the year that the employee retires. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;69 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan II &#150; Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld&#146;s employment offer letter provided her with credited service during the period she was not working for the Company between 2004 and 2006. This
enhanced pension benefit was part of a broader incentive program designed to compensate Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld for the forfeiture of benefits at her prior employer, as well as to encourage her to return to the Company. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As of December&nbsp;31, 2014, Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld is eligible to retire under the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan II. The benefits payable to
Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld before age 62 are reduced by 3% each year (maximum 20%) between age 62 and the year that she retires. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondelez Canada Inc. Retirement Plan
for Canadian Salaried Employees &#150; Mr.&nbsp;Brearton </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Beginning January&nbsp;1, 1991, this plan is not offered to newly hired Canadian employees. However,
all eligible full-time and part-time General Foods Canadian salaried employees hired before January&nbsp;1, 1991 are eligible to participate in our funded non-contributory, tax-qualified defined pension plan. All other Canadian employees hired after
December&nbsp;31, 1990 are eligible to participate in the Mondelez Canada Inc. contributory defined benefit pension plan. Benefits under this plan are payable upon retirement in the form of a monthly pension payment. Normal retirement under this
plan is defined as age 65, at which point participants are eligible to receive an unreduced benefit. Participants may elect to receive benefits before age 65 but the amount is reduced as benefits are paid over a longer period of time. Participants
under age 55 must have at least two years of service to become vested. Participants over age 55 are immediately vested. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The formula used to calculate a benefit is
equal to the following: </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Post December&nbsp;31, 1986</I> &#150; 1.25% of final average earnings (five years) less 1.4285% of the Canada Pension Plan benefit,
multiplied by credited service in the plan (maximum 35 years). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Pre January&nbsp;1, 1987 &#150; Better of: </I></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">1.25% of final average earnings (five years) less 1.4285% of the Canada Pension Plan benefit, multiplied by credited service in the plan (maximum 30 years). </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>

<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Employees hired before January&nbsp;1, 1991 are eligible to retire under this plan at age 55. The benefits payable to employees eligible to retire before age 65 are
reduced by 4% for each year (maximum 20%) between age 55 and age 60. The benefits are unreduced after age 60. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondelez Canada Inc. Supplemental Benefits Plan
&#150; Mr.&nbsp;Brearton </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Canadian Government limits the amount employees may receive from the tax-qualified pension plan. Therefore, we offer a supplemental

payable based upon the pension plan formula stated above and the amount actually payable from the Mondelez Canada Inc. Retirement Plan for Canadian Salaried Employees. Eligible employees may retire under this plan at age 55. The benefits payable to
employees eligible to retire before age 65 are reduced by 4% each year (maximum 20%) between age 55 and age 60. The benefits are unreduced after age 60. Based on the underlying calculation and Retirement Benefits Policy, it is unknown whether
Mr.&nbsp;Brearton will receive any benefit under the Mondel&#275;z Canada Inc. Supplemental Benefits Plan, so the plan is excluded from the 2014 Pension Benefits table above. </P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Reflects the number of vested performance-contingent restricted stock units granted to Ms. Rosenfeld on December&nbsp;19, 2012. Pursuant to the terms of the grant, as of December&nbsp;19, 2014, Ms. Rosenfeld no longer

shares will be distributed within 60 days following the applicable event. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan I </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Because the Code limits the amount that may be contributed to the tax-qualified defined contribution plan on behalf of an employee, we offer a supplemental defined
contribution program under the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan I. This is an unfunded program that allows eligible employees to defer a portion of their annual compensation (base salary and annual cash incentive awards) and
receive corresponding matching amounts to the extent that their contributions to the tax-qualified defined contribution plan (and the corresponding matching contributions) are limited by Code Section&nbsp;401(a)(17) or 415. Executives must defer
receipt of the payments until retirement. Executive contributions and employer matching amounts earn the same rate of return as the Interest Income Fund, which is a market rate fund available to employees in the tax-qualified defined contribution
plan. The rate of return under this investment fund in 2014 was 1.85%. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;71 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Executive Deferred Compensation Plan </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Executive Deferred Compensation Plan (the &#147;MEDCP&#148;) is a non-qualified plan that allows our NEOs to defer, on a pre-tax basis, up
to 50% of salary and up to 100% of their AIP award. The investment choices are similar to those offered to eligible employees in our U.S. 401(k) plan. Participants may elect to defer their compensation until they separate from service for purposes
of Code Section&nbsp;409A. They may also elect to receive distributions of their accounts while still employed with the Company, but the plan requires a minimum deferral period of two years. Distributions may be made in a lump sum or in annual
installments of between two and ten years. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The investment alternatives available to the executives under the MEDCP are selected by the Company and may be changed
from time to time. Participants are permitted to change their investment elections at any time on a prospective basis. The table below shows the available funds under the MEDCP and their annual rate of return for the calendar year ended
December&nbsp;31, 2014. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Potential Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The narrative and tables below describe the potential payments to each NEO upon certain terminations, including following a change in control. In accordance with SEC
rules, all information described in this section is presented as if the triggering event occurred on December&nbsp;31, 2014, except for Ms.&nbsp;West. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The
information for Ms.&nbsp;West reflects her departure in accordance with the terms of her Separation Agreement and General Release entered into on December&nbsp;16, 2014 (the &#147;Separation Agreement&#148;). Under the Separation Agreement, we will
continue to employ Ms.&nbsp;West in a full-time capacity through March&nbsp;31, 2015 and in a part-time capacity beginning April&nbsp;1, 2015 and continuing through September&nbsp;30, 2015, her last day of active employment at the Company
(&#147;Last Day Worked&#148;) (this part-time period being the &#147;Transition Period&#148;). Ms.&nbsp;West may elect to end her employment with us prior to the Last Day Worked by providing written notice (&#147;Early Termination&#148;). Pursuant
to the Separation Agreement, upon her departure, Ms.&nbsp;West will receive the following: installment payments for 24&nbsp;months following the Last Day Worked or, if applicable, the date of Early Termination (&#147;Severance Period&#148;),
totaling $697,000 (12 months of base salary); a prorated 2015 AIP award based on her full-time service from January&nbsp;1, 2015 through March&nbsp;31, 2015 and part-time service during the Transition Period (or, if earlier, upon the date of Early
Termination); a prorated share award for performance share units (&#147;PSUs&#148;) subject to the 2013-2015 performance cycle, if any, based on actual performance against the applicable performance goals (Ms.&nbsp;West will forfeit all other
outstanding PSU grants on the earlier of April&nbsp;1, 2015 or the date of Early Termination); retirement eligibility for purposes of stock options if she works through the Last Day Worked; vesting of two-thirds of the unvested 2013 restricted stock
award on September&nbsp;30, 2015 or, if earlier, upon the date of Early Termination (she will forfeit all other unvested restricted stock grants on the earlier of April&nbsp;1, 2015 or the date of Early Termination); reimbursement of 2015 financial
planning expenses not to exceed $7,500; and, unless she experiences an Early Termination, health and benefits continuation coverage for the Severance Period with eligibility for retiree medical benefits following the Severance Period to the extent
then provided to retired salaried employees. Ms.&nbsp;West is also subject to certain restrictive covenants. The restrictive covenants include the following: (i)&nbsp;she will not, without our prior written approval, work for, or provide services,
directly or indirectly, to specified competitors; and (ii)&nbsp;she will not, directly or indirectly, solicit our employees to work for another entity. In addition, Ms.&nbsp;West will maintain the confidentiality of our proprietary information, will
not disparage or discredit us or any of our affiliates and will provide a general release of any claims arising out of her employment. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;72 </FONT></P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Involuntary Termination Without Cause (Non-Change in Control Event) </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We do not have existing employment or separation agreements with our NEOs that dictate the terms of the NEO&#146;s departure from the Company. However, in the event an
NEO is involuntarily terminated without cause outside of a change in control event, we expect that in most cases our Compensation Committee would offer separation benefits as consideration for protections we would likely seek &#150; such as a
release of claims and having the departing NEO enter into non-compete, non-solicitation and confidentiality agreements. For our U.S. salaried employees, we maintain a severance plan that provides severance pay of up to 12 months based on service
where the employee&#146;s job is eliminated. We would expect to treat our NEOs at least comparably to other U.S. salaried employees who leave the Company without cause due to our actions, and our treatment of Ms.&nbsp;West is consistent with this
approach. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following chart reflects the typical separation benefits that may be offered to an NEO who is involuntarily terminated without cause. Actual terms
and conditions would be determined by our Compensation Committee based on the particular facts in a specific case. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="20%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="3%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="77%"></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Typical Severance Benefits</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;CEO: 24 months of base salary.</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;All other NEOs: 12 months of base salary.</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Payment may be in a lump sum or in salary
continuation and, if subject to Code Section 409A, payment is delayed 6 months for an NEO who is a &#147;specified employee&#148;.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Pension, Health and Welfare Benefits</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If salary continuation, pension crediting continues
during that period; health and welfare benefits coverage also continues.</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If no salary continuation, no continuation of
benefits.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Perquisites</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Continuation of financial counseling and car
allowances for 24 months for the CEO and 12 months for the other NEOs.</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Outplacement services up to 12 months.</P></TD></TR>

<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Treatment of AIP Award</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Payment of prorated award based on actual business performance results and target
individual performance.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Treatment of PSU Grants</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;NEO&#146;s outstanding PSU grants are forfeited and our Compensation Committee may
exercise discretion to make awards subject at all times to actual Company performance.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Treatment of Other Equity Grants</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Restricted stock and unvested stock option grants
are forfeited and our Compensation Committee may exercise discretion to accelerate vesting.</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For the CEO, all outstanding performance-contingent
restricted stock units vested on December 19, 2014 and, upon termination, she will receive shares for the vested units on December&nbsp;19, 2015, which is the same time she would otherwise receive the shares if she was still employed.</P></TD></TR>

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(3)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Pursuant to the Separation Agreement, Ms.&nbsp;West will receive a prorated 2013-2015 PSU award based on the Company&#146;s actual performance during the three-year performance cycle. The prorated award, if any, is
based on the number of full months of employment from January&nbsp;1, 2013 through the earlier of March&nbsp;31, 2015 or date of Early Termination and will be paid no later than March&nbsp;15, 2016 following the Compensation Committee&#146;s
certification of the Company&#146;s performance. The amount in the table above reflects the prorated 2013-2015 PSU grant through March&nbsp;31, 2015, assuming a performance rating of 100%, and is based on a December&nbsp;31, 2014 closing stock price
of $36.33. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(4)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Pursuant to the Separation Agreement, Ms.&nbsp;West receives two-thirds of her 2013 annual restricted stock grant on September&nbsp;30, 2015 assuming she does not experience an Early Termination prior to
December&nbsp;31, 2014. The amount reflects the prorated 2013 annual restricted stock grant based on a December&nbsp;31, 2014 closing stock price of $36.33. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(5)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Pursuant to the Separation Agreement, assuming Ms.&nbsp;West does not experience an Early Termination, she is &#147;retirement eligible&#148; for purposes of her outstanding unvested stock options resulting in all
outstanding unvested stock options continuing to vest in accordance with the original vesting schedule. The amount reflects the intrinsic value of all outstanding unvested stock options as of March&nbsp;1, 2015 based on a December&nbsp;31, 2014
closing stock price of $36.33. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(6)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The reflected continuation of benefits and coverage is based on our typical practice; however, our Compensation Committee would determine the terms and conditions of an individual separation agreement. The amounts
reflect 24 months of medical, dental, vision, long-term disability and life insurance coverage for Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld, and 12 months of medical, dental, vision, long-term disability and life insurance coverage for the other NEOs except
Ms.&nbsp;West. The amount also includes a retiree medical benefit with a present value of $72,000 for Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld and $167,000 for Mr.&nbsp;Brearton as both would be eligible for retiree medical benefits at the end of the coverage period.
Pursuant to the Separation Agreement, assuming Ms.&nbsp;West does not experience an Early Termination, she receives 24 months of medical, dental, vision, long-term disability and life insurance coverage and becomes eligible for a retiree medical
benefit with a present value of $147,000 at the end of the 24&nbsp;month coverage period, which is reflected in the amount. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Change in Control Arrangements </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We maintain a Change in Control Plan (the
&#147;CIC Plan&#148;) for senior executive officers, including the NEOs, which provides for certain benefits upon an involuntary termination of employment without &#147;Cause&#148; or voluntary termination for &#147;Good Reason&#148; within two
years following a change in control. Additionally, to receive any benefits under the CIC Plan, all participants must execute and abide by certain restrictive covenants, including a non-compete and non-solicitation. The key elements of the CIC Plan
are described in the table below. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="18%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="80%"></TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#4c4c4c" STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Plan Element</FONT></B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Description</FONT></B></FONT></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Definition&nbsp;of&nbsp;Change</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">in&nbsp;Control (&#147;CIC&#148;)</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Subject to certain exceptions, the occurrence of one of the
conditions below:</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Acquisition of 20% or more of our outstanding voting
securities;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Changes to Board membership during any consecutive
24-month period that results in less than 50% of the current Board members elected to the Board;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our merger or consolidation with another company,
and</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:4.25em; text-indent:-2.00em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;we are not the surviving
company; or</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:4.25em; text-indent:-2.00em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">b)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;the other entity
owns 50% or more of our outstanding voting securities; or</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Complete liquidation of Mondel&#275;z International
or the sale of all or substantially all of our assets.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Definition of &#147;Cause&#148;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Continued failure to substantially perform the
participant&#146;s job duties (other than resulting from incapacity due to disability);</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gross negligence, dishonesty or violation of any
reasonable rule or regulation of the Company where the violation results in significant damage to the Company; or</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Engaging in other conduct which adversely reflects
on Company in any material respect.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Definition of &#147;Good Reason&#148;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Material reduction in job duties;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Material reduction in compensation;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Relocation beyond 50 miles; or</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Increased business travel.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Severance and Benefits Amounts</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;CEO: 2.99 times base salary plus target annual
incentive;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;All other NEOs: two times base salary plus target
annual incentive;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Additional credited years of pension service and
welfare benefits equal to three years for the CEO and two years for the other NEOs;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Continuation of financial counseling and car
allowances for three years for the CEO and two years for the other NEOs; and</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Outplacement services up to two years following the
CIC.</P></TD></TR></TABLE>
